3.4 Normalized classiÔ¨Åer-free guidance

The diffusion model may ignore the conditional input and produce results uncorrelated with this input. One way to address this is the classiÔ¨Åer-free guidance [21], which considers p(xt|y) along with p(y|xt) during sampling. The gradient of the log-probability p(y|xt) can be estimated as

‚àáxt log p (y|xt) ‚àù ‚àáxt log p (xt|y) ‚àí ‚àáxt log p (xt) ‚àù Œ∏ (xt|y) ‚àí Œ∏ (xt) .

(6)

During sampling, we can estimate noise with a given condition y and a null condition ‚àÖ respectively, and generate samples further away from Œ∏(xt|‚àÖ):

ÀÜŒ∏ (xt|y) = Œ∏ (xt|y) + w ¬∑ ( Œ∏ (xt|y) ‚àí Œ∏ (xt|‚àÖ)) ,

(7)

where w ‚â• 0 controls the guidance strengths. Such classiÔ¨Åer-free guidance would trade off the sampling diversity to improve the quality of individual samples.

However, we observe that such a sampling procedure causes the mean and variance shift which hinders the subsequent denoising. To be concrete, the guided noise sample ÀÜŒ∏ (xt|y) from Equation 7 takes the mean as ¬µÀÜ = ¬µ + w(¬µ ‚àí ¬µ‚àÖ), indicating that there is a mean shift brought by the classiÔ¨Åerfree guidance. Similarly, the variance of the noise sample shifts as œÉÀÜ2 = (1 + w)2œÉ2 + w2œÉ‚àÖ2 with an assumption that Œ∏ (xt|y) and Œ∏ (xt|‚àÖ) are independent variables. Such statistics shift will accumulate through all the T diffusion denoising steps, leading to over-saturated images with
over-smoothed textures.

